1.Inspect Pod Events: Check Exit Code
kubectl get pod <pod> -o jsonpath='{.status.containerStatuses[0].state.terminated.exitCode}'
kubectl logs <pod> --previous

Retrieves output from the last run before it restarted.

Validate Probes

Temporarily disable or loosen livenessProbe/readinessProbe

Increase initialDelaySeconds if startup is slow

Confirm Command/Entrypoint
Ensure your command and args in the Pod spec actually launch your service (vs. exiting immediately).

Run Interactively

kubectl run debug --image=<your-image> --restart=Never --attach --tty -- bash
Manually start your process to see any hidden errors.

Review Resource Limits
If you see OOMKills, raise your container’s memory/CPU limits.

Verify Config & Mounts
Check that ConfigMaps, Secrets, and volume mounts are correct and contain the files/env‑vars your app needs.

